## 🧠 PART 1 — React Concepts You Must Know

### 1.1 What is JSX?

Every `.jsx` file mixes HTML and JavaScript together. This is called **JSX**.

```jsx
// This looks like HTML but it's actually JavaScript
function Hero() {
  return (
    <section id="home">
      <h1>Understand bond risk in seconds</h1>
    </section>
  );
}
```

> **Rule:** Every component must return a **single root element**. Use `<>...</>` (called a **Fragment**) to wrap multiple elements without adding an extra div.

---

### 1.2 Components

A **component** is just a JavaScript function that returns JSX.

In your project, every file in `src/components/` and `src/pages/` is a component.

```jsx
// Navbar.jsx - a component
function Navbar({ onStartRating }) {
  return <header>...</header>;
}

export default Navbar; // must export it to use it elsewhere
```

**Naming convention:** Always start with a Capital letter. `navbar` would be wrong — React would treat it as a regular HTML tag.

---

### 1.3 Props (Properties)

Props are how you **pass data from a parent component to a child component**. They go in like HTML attributes.

```jsx
// Parent (App.jsx) passes a function down to Navbar
<Navbar onStartRating={openTermsModal} />

// Child (Navbar.jsx) receives it in its function argument
function Navbar({ onStartRating }) {
  return (
    <button onClick={onStartRating}>Start Rating</button>
  );
}
```

In your project this pattern appears everywhere:
- `App.jsx` → `Navbar` passes `onStartRating`
- `App.jsx` → `LandingPage` passes `onStartRating`
- `App.jsx` → `TermsConsentModal` passes `isOpen`, `onClose`, `onAccept`

**Spread props** — in `App.jsx`, when rendering static pages:
```jsx
<StaticPage {...staticPages.about} />
// This is shorthand for:
<StaticPage eyebrow="Company" title="About Rate My Bond" description={[...]} />
```

---

### 1.4 useState — The Most Important Hook

`useState` lets a component **remember information** between renders.

```jsx
const [menuOpen, setMenuOpen] = useState(false);
//     ↑ current value   ↑ function to update it   ↑ initial value
```

**Real examples in your code:**

```jsx
// Navbar.jsx — remembers if mobile menu is open or closed
const [menuOpen, setMenuOpen] = useState(false);

// Toggle it:
onClick={() => setMenuOpen((value) => !value)}
```

```jsx
// BondCalculatorPage.jsx — stores all form input values
const [values, setValues] = useState(emptyValues);

// Update a specific field:
const updateValue = (fieldId, nextValue) => {
  setValues((current) => ({
    ...current,           // keep all existing values
    [fieldId]: nextValue, // update just this one field
  }));
};
```

> **Key rule:** Never mutate state directly (`values.field = "x"` is WRONG). Always call the setter function.

---

### 1.5 useEffect — Running Code at the Right Time

`useEffect` runs **side effects** — code that happens AFTER the component renders. Common uses: fetching data, reading from localStorage, subscriptions.

```jsx
// SitePreferencesBanner.jsx — check localStorage when the component first loads
useEffect(() => {
  const saved = window.localStorage.getItem("rate-my-bond-cookie-consent");
  if (!saved) {
    setIsConsentOpen(true); // show the banner if no consent saved
  }
}, []); // ← the empty [] means "run only once, when component mounts"
```

```jsx
// SignInPage.jsx — subscribe to Firebase auth state changes
useEffect(() => {
  const unsubscribe = onAuthStateChanged(auth, (nextUser) => {
    setUser(nextUser);
  });
  return unsubscribe; // ← cleanup function: unsubscribe when component unmounts
}, []);
```

```jsx
// TermsConsentModal.jsx — reset the checkbox every time the modal opens/closes
useEffect(() => {
  if (!isOpen) setAccepted(false);
}, [isOpen]); // ← run whenever 'isOpen' changes
```

**The dependency array `[]` controls when useEffect runs:**
- `[]` → run once on mount
- `[someValue]` → run whenever `someValue` changes
- no array → run after every render (usually unwanted)

---

### 1.6 Conditional Rendering

Showing or hiding elements based on state/props.

```jsx
// Pattern 1: Ternary (if/else)
{menuOpen ? <MobileMenu /> : null}

// Pattern 2: Short-circuit (if only)
{errorMessage && <p>{errorMessage}</p>}

// Pattern 3: Early return (used in TermsConsentModal)
if (!isOpen) return null;
```

---

### 1.7 Lists and the key Prop

When you render an array, React needs a unique `key` on each item.

```jsx
// Navbar.jsx
{navItems.map((item) => (
  <Link key={item.label} to={item.to}>
    {item.label}
  </Link>
))}
```

> **Why keys?** React uses them to track which items changed/added/removed when the list re-renders. Without `key`, React can't do this efficiently and might show wrong data.

---

### 1.8 Event Handling

```jsx
// onClick - button click
<button onClick={handleGoogleSignIn}>Sign in</button>

// onChange - input/select change
<select onChange={(event) => onChange(field.id, event.target.value)}>

// Event with inline arrow function
<button onClick={() => setMenuOpen(false)}>Close</button>
```

---

## 🗺 PART 2 — How React Router Works

React Router makes your app behave like it has multiple pages, **without actually reloading the browser**.

### 2.1 Setup (main.jsx)

```jsx
ReactDOM.createRoot(document.getElementById("root")).render(
  <React.StrictMode>
    <BrowserRouter>      {/* ← wraps the whole app */}
      <App />
    </BrowserRouter>
  </React.StrictMode>
);
```

`BrowserRouter` gives the whole app access to routing.

### 2.2 Defining Routes (App.jsx)

```jsx
<Routes>
  <Route path="/"            element={<LandingPage />} />
  <Route path="/calculator"  element={<BondCalculatorPage />} />
  <Route path="/signin"      element={<SignInPage />} />
  <Route path="/about"       element={<StaticPage {...staticPages.about} />} />
  <Route path="*"            element={<LandingPage />} /> {/* 404 fallback */}
</Routes>
```

`path="*"` is the wildcard — it catches any URL that doesn't match the others.

### 2.3 Navigation

```jsx
// Link — like <a href> but doesn't reload the page
import { Link } from "react-router-dom";
<Link to="/calculator">Open calculator</Link>

// useNavigate — programmatic navigation (navigate in code)
const navigate = useNavigate();
navigate("/calculator"); // used in acceptTermsAndContinue()
```

### 2.4 Reading the Current URL (useLocation)

```jsx
// App.jsx — ScrollToHash component
const location = useLocation();

useEffect(() => {
  if (location.hash) {
    // e.g. location.hash = "#how-it-works"
    const id = location.hash.replace("#", "");
    document.getElementById(id)?.scrollIntoView({ behavior: "smooth" });
  }
}, [location.hash, location.pathname]);
```

This is how clicking "How it Works" in the Navbar smoothly scrolls to that section on the landing page.

---

## 🔥 PART 3 — Firebase Authentication

Firebase is Google's backend service. You used it for **Google Sign-In** (OAuth).

### 3.1 Configuration (lib/firebase.js)

```js
const firebaseConfig = {
  apiKey: import.meta.env.VITE_FIREBASE_API_KEY,   // reads from .env file
  authDomain: import.meta.env.VITE_FIREBASE_AUTH_DOMAIN,
  // ...
};
```

`import.meta.env.VITE_*` is how Vite reads environment variables from `.env`. The `VITE_` prefix is required — Vite won't expose variables without it.

**Defensive initialisation:**
```js
const hasFirebaseConfig = Object.values(firebaseConfig).every(Boolean);

if (hasFirebaseConfig) {
  const app = getApps().length ? getApp() : initializeApp(firebaseConfig);
  auth = getAuth(app);
  googleProvider = new GoogleAuthProvider();
}
```

`getApps().length ? getApp() : initializeApp(...)` — This prevents initializing Firebase twice (which would crash it). If it's already initialized, get the existing instance.

### 3.2 Sign In / Sign Out (SignInPage.jsx)

```js
// Sign in with Google popup
await signInWithPopup(auth, googleProvider);

// Sign out
await signOut(auth);

// Listen for auth state changes (is user logged in or not?)
onAuthStateChanged(auth, (nextUser) => {
  setUser(nextUser); // nextUser is null if signed out
});
```

The `onAuthStateChanged` listener is a **subscription** — it constantly watches Firebase and updates your component whenever the sign-in status changes. The `return unsubscribe` in your `useEffect` cleanup ensures this listener is removed when the page is unmounted.

