## ⚙️ PART 4 — The Bond Rating Engine (ratingModel.js + BondCalculatorPage.jsx)

This is the brain of your application.

### 4.1 Data Structure (ratingModel.js)

You defined all your data as **exported JavaScript objects/arrays**:

```js
export const groupWeights = {
  financialStrength: 40,   // most important factor (40%)
  ratios: 25,
  cashFlow: 20,
  bondStructure: 10,
  riskFlags: 5,
};
```

```js
export const requiredSections = [
  {
    id: "financialStrength",
    title: "Financial Strength",
    fields: [
      {
        id: "totalDebtLevel",
        label: "Total Debt Level",
        type: "select",
        group: "financialStrength",
        options: [
          { label: "Very Low", score: 5 },
          { label: "Low", score: 4 },
          // ...
        ],
      },
    ],
  },
  // ...
];
```

Each field has:
- `id` — unique identifier (used as the form state key)
- `label` — what the user sees
- `type` — `"select"` or `"searchable"`
- `group` — which weight category it belongs to
- `options` — array of choices, each with a `score` (1–5)

### 4.2 The Scoring Algorithm (BondCalculatorPage.jsx)

**Step 1 — Build empty state from data:**
```js
const emptyValues = [...requiredFields, ...optionalFields].reduce(
  (accumulator, field) => ({
    ...accumulator,
    [field.id]: "",
  }),
  {}
);
// Result: { totalDebtLevel: "", couponRate: "", ... }
```

`reduce` is an array method that "reduces" an array to a single value. Here it builds an object.

**Step 2 — Calculate per-group scores:**
```js
const groupBreakdown = Object.entries(groupWeights).map(([group, weight]) => {
  const fields = requiredFields.filter(f => f.group === group);
  const scores = fields.map(f => findScore(f, values[f.id])).filter(Boolean);
  const normalized = scores.length ? (sum(scores) / scores.length) * 20 : 0;
  // Scores are 1–5, multiply by 20 to get 20–100 scale

  return {
    group, weight,
    score: normalized,
    weightedScore: (normalized * weight) / 100,
  };
});
```

**Step 3 — Combine weighted scores:**
```js
const requiredScore = groupBreakdown.reduce(
  (total, item) => total + item.weightedScore, 0
);
// This is a weighted average
```

**Step 4 — Optional fields add a refinement adjustment (+/- 5 points):**
```js
const refinementAdjustment = Math.max(-5, Math.min(5, (optionalAverage - 3) * 2.5));
```

**Step 5 — Map final score → rating band:**
```js
function getRatingBand(score) {
  if (score >= 85) return "AAA";
  if (score >= 75) return "AA";
  if (score >= 65) return "A";
  if (score >= 55) return "BBB";
  if (score >= 45) return "BB";
  return "B / Junk";
}
```

**Step 6 — Confidence % (how complete the form is):**
```js
confidence: Math.round(
  (requiredCompletion / requiredFields.length) * 65 + optionalCompletion * 35
);
// Required fields = 65% of confidence, optional = 35%
```

### 4.3 The FieldControl Component

A mini-component inside the calculator page that renders either a `<select>` or a searchable `<input>` with a `<datalist>`:

```jsx
function FieldControl({ field, value, onChange }) {
  if (field.type === "searchable") {
    return (
      <>
        <input list="issuer-options" value={value} ... />
        <datalist id="issuer-options">
          {issuerOptions.map(issuer => <option key={issuer} value={issuer} />)}
        </datalist>
      </>
    );
  }
  return <select>...</select>;
}
```

`<datalist>` is a native HTML element that provides autocomplete suggestions for an `<input>`.

---

## 🍪 PART 5 — Cookie Consent Banner (SitePreferencesBanner.jsx)

This is a GDPR-compliant cookie preferences system. It uses `localStorage` to persist the user's choice.

### Key Concepts:

**localStorage** — browser storage that survives page refreshes:
```js
// Save to localStorage
window.localStorage.setItem("key", JSON.stringify(data));

// Read from localStorage
const saved = window.localStorage.getItem("key");
const parsed = JSON.parse(saved);
```

**The Toggle component** — a custom checkbox built from scratch:
```jsx
function Toggle({ checked, onChange, disabled = false }) {
  return (
    <button
      role="switch"        // ARIA role for accessibility
      aria-checked={checked}
      onClick={onChange}
    >
      <span className={checked ? "translate-x-6" : "translate-x-1"} />
      {/* The dot slides left/right using CSS transforms */}
    </button>
  );
}
```

**Dynamic object key update:**
```js
const togglePreference = (key) => {
  setPreferences((current) => ({
    ...current,
    [key]: !current[key], // [key] is a "computed property name"
  }));
};
// togglePreference("analytics") → flips the analytics value
```

---

## 📄 PART 6 — StaticPage (Reusable Pattern)

This is a great example of a **data-driven component**. Instead of creating 5 separate page components (About, Privacy, Terms, Cookies, Help), you created ONE component that accepts data as props.

```jsx
// ONE component handles ALL these pages
function StaticPage({ eyebrow, title, description }) {
  const isStructuredDescription = Array.isArray(description);

  return (
    <main>
      <h1>{title}</h1>
      {isStructuredDescription
        ? description.map(section => <section>...</section>)
        : <p>{description}</p>
      }
    </main>
  );
}
```

All the page content lives in `App.jsx` as a data object:
```js
const staticPages = {
  about: { title: "About Rate My Bond", description: [...], eyebrow: "Company" },
  privacy: { title: "Privacy Policy", description: [...], eyebrow: "Legal" },
  // ...
};
```

This is called the **"render props" / data-driven UI** pattern and it's used heavily in professional codebases.

