## 🎨 PART 7 — Tailwind CSS

Tailwind CSS lets you style HTML elements using utility class names instead of writing separate CSS files.

### Common Classes Used in Your Project

| Class | What it does |
|---|---|
| `flex`, `grid` | Layout modes |
| `items-center`, `justify-between` | Alignment |
| `gap-4` | Space between flex/grid items |
| `px-6`, `py-4` | Horizontal & vertical padding |
| `rounded-full`, `rounded-2xl` | Border radius |
| `text-white`, `text-sm`, `font-semibold` | Typography |
| `border`, `border-white/10` | Border (with opacity) |
| `bg-white/5` | Background (5% white opacity) |
| `transition`, `hover:scale-[1.02]` | Animation on hover |
| `hidden md:flex` | Hidden on mobile, flex on desktop |
| `sticky top-0 z-50` | Sticky positioning |
| `fixed inset-0` | Full-screen overlay |
| `backdrop-blur-xl` | Glassmorphism blur effect |

### Responsive Design

Tailwind uses **breakpoint prefixes**:
```jsx
// default = mobile, md: = desktop
className="hidden md:flex"
// Hidden on mobile, flex on screens >= 768px

className="grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2"
// 1 column on mobile, 2 columns on large screens
```

