## 🏛 PART 9 — Architecture Patterns Used

### 9.1 Lifting State Up

When multiple components need the same state, you **lift it up** to their common parent.

```jsx
// App.jsx controls the modal state
const [isTermsModalOpen, setIsTermsModalOpen] = useState(false);

// It passes the opener DOWN to Navbar AND LandingPage
<Navbar onStartRating={openTermsModal} />
<LandingPage onStartRating={openTermsModal} />

// The modal itself also lives in App
<TermsConsentModal isOpen={isTermsModalOpen} ... />
```

Both `Navbar` and `LandingPage` can open the same modal because the state lives in their shared parent `App`.

### 9.2 Single Responsibility Components

Each component does ONE thing:
- `Logo.jsx` → renders the logo
- `Hero.jsx` → the hero section
- `FieldControl.jsx` → renders one form field
- `Toggle.jsx` → renders one toggle switch

### 9.3 Data Separated from UI

Your data (`ratingModel.js`) is completely separate from the UI (`BondCalculatorPage.jsx`). The UI just reads from the data. This means if you want to add a new rating field, you only edit `ratingModel.js` — the UI automatically picks it up.

### 9.4 Derived State (vs Stored State)

In `BondCalculatorPage.jsx`:
```js
// STORED state — only the raw input values
const [values, setValues] = useState(emptyValues);

// DERIVED state — calculated from values on every render
const model = calculateModel(values);
```

`model` is never stored in `useState`. It's recalculated every time `values` changes. This is a best practice — don't store things you can calculate.

